Identify the dependence in the following code:
```
S1: b = a;
S2: a = 1;
```

Consider this loop:
```c
for (i=0; i<100; i++) 
    a[i] = a[i] + 100;
```
Is this loop parallelizable?

Evaluate the following code for parallelization:
```c
for (i=0; i<100; i++)
    a[i] = f(a[i-1]);
```

Why might a compiler be unable to parallelize the following loop?
```c
for (i=0; i<100; i++)
    a[i] = f(a[index[i]]);
```

Analyze this loop nest:
```c
for (i=0; i<100; i++)
    for (j=0; j<100; j++)
        a[i][j] = f(a[i][j-1]);
```
Which statement is true?

In Example 16, how was the loop parallelized?
```c
for (i=1; i<N; i++) {
    a[i] = b[i] + c[i];
    d[i] = a[i-1] + d[i];
}
```

In Example 12, why can the outer loop be parallelized?
```c
for (i=0; i<100; i++)
    for (j=0; j<100; j++)
        a[i][j] = f(a[i][j-1]);
```

In the following code, what type of dependence exists between S1 and S2?
```
S1: a = 1;
S2: a = 2;
```

In Example 13, why is loop interchange beneficial?
```c
for (j=0; j<100; j++)
    for (i=0; i<100; i++)
        a[i][j] = f(a[i][j-1]);
```
